x4freetext: The targets of the isotopically enriched Mg-24,
enrichment 99.7% and Mg-26, enrichment 99.77% were
used. Both magnesium targets of 100+-20-mug/cm**2
thickness were evaporated on 25-mug/cm**2 thick
carbon backings with a thin gold layer, about 1-mug/
.Microscopic EFR-DWBA and CCBA analysis with
shell-model wave functions.
Typical momentum spectrum for the transfer reaction
was observed.
the Saclay quadrupole-dipole-dipole-dipole(Q3D)
magnetic spectrometer and two-stage gas counter of
60 cm effective length. The first stage was
a transmission resistive wire gas counter. The second
counter measured the residual energy E(g) of the
detected particles-for outgoing reaction products of
the (O-18,O-16) reaction
the elastic and inelastic scattering of
O-16 on Mg-26 was measured with a multi-telescope
counter mounted in a scattering chamber. This detector
consisted of a delta-E resistive wire gas counter
followed by a 5 cm long surface barrier detector.
the Saclay super FN tandem accelerator.
All data are corrected for dead time losses which
were typically 2% and always smaller than 8%.
*By authors*.Relative cross sections were obtained by
normalizing the number of counts of every measurement
to the number of the counts of elastically scattered
particles detected in a surface barrier detector
located at 30-degree in the scattering chamber.
*By authors*.Absolute cross sections were obtained by
normalizing the relative cross sections to the forward
elastic scattering data assumed to be pure Rutherford
scattering.
.Digitizing error of data.
.Digitizing error of angle.
.BY CAJAD.
fig 2 and 3
.The overall uncertainty of the absolute cross
sections of the (O-18,O-16) measurements is estimated
to be 15% resulting from uncertainties in the dead time
correction factors, the charge state distribution,
statistical error due to low counting rate and the
deviation of the measured elastic scattering and the
calculated Rutherford cross sections at forward angles.

the  1.81 MeV inelastic peak of Mg-26 overlaps with the
oxygen impurity peak, a WO(3) target was used to
measured the oxygen contribution which was subtracted
from the spectra.
